		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">psycopathicteen wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I have a few questions about screen resolutions.<br /><br />1) Why is standard resolution sometimes called 480i when there are 448 visible lines?</div><br />Please see <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Overscan" class="postlink">Overscan on Wikipedia</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safe_area" class="postlink">Safe area on Wikipedia</a>, and <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Overscan" class="postlink">Overscan on wiki.nesdev.com</a>.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">2) How many pixels do HDTV's sample from an NTSC (or PAL) signal per line.</div><br />The standard (Rec. 601) is 720 samples at 13.5 MHz, of which 704 are picture (such that 704x480 covers 4:3) and 16 are "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nominal_analogue_blanking" class="postlink">nominal analog blanking</a>", which is outside even the overscan area. These 704 samples cover 280 pixels of the NES or Super NES video signal.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I think the best NTSC to HDTV conversion would have to sample the NTSC signal at a multiple of 170, possible 3x or 4x.</div>
<br />Apparently, the standard is to demodulate the chroma, which converts the composite video to component video, in the analog domain before sampling.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
