	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Fsc is defined as 39.3750/11 MHz, so 3.75*Fsc is 13.4233 MHz, just a hair slow. F<span style="font-size: 84%; line-height: normal">601</span> = 13.5000 MHz was chosen because it is exactly 858 times the scanline frequency on NTSC (Fsc/227.5) and exactly 864 times the scanline frequency on PAL (15625 Hz). The exact ratio is F<span style="font-size: 84%; line-height: normal">601</span> = 132/35 * Fsc = 3.7714 * Fsc.
<br />
<br />Rec. 601 also defines a frequency for square pixel sampling on NTSC. This is 24/7 * Fsc (12.2727 MHz) for 640x480i SDTV, or 12/7 * Fsc (6.13636 MHz) for 320x240p LDTV. So Genesis pixels (15/8 * Fsc = 6.71165 MHz) are narrow, and Neo Geo pixels (6.00000 MHz) are a hair wide.
<br />
<br />Of course, the other way to do this is to sample at 4 * Fsc. This is, for example, the dot clock rate for Apple II video.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


